FuzzMing
Three Decisions That Define the Architecture
Decision 1 — Component split or flat structure
Decision 2 — Use case granularity
Decision 3 — Where dependency injection lives
Context
FuzzMing is a fuzzing assistant for Solidity smart contracts. It runs a feedback loop: it asks an LLM
to generate invariants, runs Foundry to fuzz them, reads the results, and loops until it finds a bug,
achieves full coverage, or exhausts its round budget.
The system has a single flow — one session, one loop, one outcome. This simplicity is precisely
what makes the architectural decisions non-trivial: when a system has one flow, it is tempting to
write it as one flat sequence of calls. Every decision below is about why that temptation was resisted
and what we chose instead.
The three decisions: 1 — Split into components or keep flat. 2 — One use case per action or one
use case for the whole flow. 3 — Where to wire dependencies together.
Decision 1 — Component Split or Flat
Structure
The Question
FuzzMing has one flow. Should the code be split into self-contained components — Orchestrator,
LLMEngine, FoundryEngine, Reader, Executor, Reporter — or should it live as a flat set of classes
in a single layer with no internal boundaries?
Decision 1 — How to organise the codebase
✗ Rejected — Flat structure — all classes in one layer, no component boundaries, shared access
to everything.
✓ CHOSEN — Component split — seven self-contained components, each owning its data needs,
communicating only through defined interfaces.
Why this choice: FuzzMing has one flow but seven distinct responsibilities. Without component
boundaries, any class can call any other class, read any file, and write any file. A bug in how the LLM
output is parsed can accidentally corrupt the coverage data. A change to how Foundry is invoked
requires understanding the entire codebase. The component split enforces that each responsibility
has one owner, one boundary, and one defined contract with the outside world.
What the Split Looks Like
Seven components. Each one is self-sufficient — it pulls its own inputs and pushes its own outputs.
No component calls another directly. The Orchestrator only sequences; it never sees data artifacts.
src/
interfaces/ // All shared I* contracts — owned by no component
orchestrator/ // Sequences the loop. Termination decisions only.
llm/ // Pulls context, calls LLM, pushes invariants and config.
foundry/ // Runs forge, reads output, returns outcome signal.
reader/ // Read-only gateway. Single source of all file reads.
executor/ // Write-only gateway. Single source of all file writes.
reporter/ // Formats terminal and CI output at session end.
entry/ // CLI and CI/CD entry points — protocol translation only.
composition/ // Single wiring point. The only file importing concrete types.
Why Not Flat
A flat structure collapses two problems onto each other that should be kept separate:
• Who owns what data. In a flat structure, any class can read any file. Reader and Executor
exist specifically to make file access explicit and traceable — Reader is the only class that
calls fs.readFileSync, Executor is the only class that calls fs.writeFileSync. Without them, a
future developer adds one file read inside what should be a pure decision class and the
read/write contract is silently broken.
• What calls what. In a flat structure, LLMEngine can call FoundryEngine directly. The
architecture document's hard rule — no component calls another component directly — is
unenforceable without boundaries. The Orchestrator becomes a fat coordinator because
there is nothing to stop it accumulating data handling alongside its sequencing responsibility.
The Concrete Consequence
The component split means each component can be tested in isolation. LLMEngine tests inject a
mock ILLMGateway and a mock IReaderPort — no real files, no real LLM, no real Foundry.
FoundryEngine tests inject a mock IForgeRunnerPort — no subprocess. The Orchestrator tests
inject mock ILLMEnginePort and IFoundryEnginePort — the Orchestrator's sequencing logic is
verified without any component doing real work.
Decision 2 — Use Case Granularity
The Question
FuzzMing has one flow. How granular should use cases be? Three positions were considered: one
use case for the entire flow, one use case per component, or one use case per distinct action.
Decision 2 — Use case granularity
✗ Rejected — One use case for the whole system — RunFuzzMingSession contains the entire
flow end to end.
✗ Rejected — One use case per component — LLMEngine has one use case, FoundryEngine has
one use case, etc.
✓ CHOSEN — One use case per distinct action — each named action (AssemblePrompt,
EvaluateOutcome, CheckTermination, etc.) is its own class with one execute() method.
Why this choice: One use case for the whole system is untestable and accumulates all reasons to
change in one place. One use case per component is better but still mixes multiple decisions inside
one class — LLMEngine would have prompt assembly, LLM calling, and config generation all in one
execute(), which means changing the prompt strategy requires touching the same class as changing
the config parser. One use case per action keeps each decision independently testable,
independently nameable, and independently replaceable.
The Problem With One Use Case for the Whole Flow
Because FuzzMing has one flow it is tempting to write:
class RunFuzzMingSession {
execute(request: ISessionRequest): void {
// pull contract context
// assemble prompt
// call LLM
// write invariants
// run forge
// parse output
// check termination
// loop or stop
}
}
This looks clean but it is a single class with eight reasons to change, zero internal contracts, and no
way to test prompt assembly without also spawning a Foundry process. It is the flat structure
problem applied to the use case layer.
The Problem With One Use Case Per Component
One step better, but still too coarse. Consider what LLMEngine's single use case would own:
class RunLLMEngine {
execute(signal: IRoundSignal): ILLMSignal {
// AssemblePrompt logic -- changes when context weighting changes
// GenerateInvariants logic -- changes when LLM parsing changes
// AdaptFoundryConfig logic -- changes when config format changes
}
}
Three distinct decisions, three independent reasons to change, all in one class. Changing how
coverage gaps are weighted in the prompt requires reading through the same class as changing
how the LLM response is parsed. The boundaries between decisions are invisible.
One Use Case Per Action — The Chosen Approach
Each distinct decision or action is its own class with a single execute() method. The rule: if you can
name it in one sentence and a non-technical stakeholder would understand it, it is a use case.
Component Use Case What It Decides or Does
Orchestrator InitialiseSession Builds ISessionState from ISessionRequest — once per
session
Orchestrator RunRound Sends IRoundSignal to llmPort and foundryPort, awaits
results
Orchestrator CheckTermination bug | fullCoverage | exhausted | continue — after every
round
LLMEngine AssemblePrompt What context to include, how to weight gaps vs failures
LLMEngine GenerateInvariants Calls LLM gateway, parses Solidity output into
IInvariantSet
LLMEngine AdaptFoundryConfig Calls LLM gateway, parses config output into
IFoundryConfig
FoundryEngine RunFuzzer Executes forge test, captures exit code and stdout
FoundryEngine RunCoverage Executes forge coverage — only on clean fuzzer pass
FoundryEngine EvaluateOutcome bug | pass | fullCoverage — the most critical decision in
the system
Reporter FormatBugReport Formats falsified invariant and shrunk call sequence
Reporter FormatExhaustedReport Formats remaining uncovered lines with source context
Reporter FormatCoverageReport Formats full coverage summary
Reporter FormatDevTestFailure Formats developer test failure name and assertion
Reader and Executor — No Use Cases
Reader and Executor are the exception. Neither has a use case layer because neither makes
decisions. Reader converts bytes into structured types — that is a parser, not a use case. Executor
materialises structured objects onto disk — that is a writer, not a use case.
The test: A use case orchestrates a decision. A parser converts. A writer materialises. If a class
makes no decision and contains no business logic, it does not belong in use_cases/ regardless of
how important it is.
Decision 3 — Where Dependency Injection
Lives
The Question
Every component depends on interfaces. Concrete implementations must be injected somewhere.
The question is where — at the point of use, distributed across multiple files, or in a single dedicated
place.
Decision 3 — Where to wire dependencies
✗ Rejected — Inline instantiation — each class creates its own dependencies with new inside its
constructor or methods.
✗ Rejected — Distributed wiring — entry points or component facades each wire their own piece
of the graph.
✓ CHOSEN — Single composition root — one file, src/composition/CompositionRoot.ts,
instantiates all concrete types and wires the entire graph.
Why this choice: Inline instantiation couples every class to its concrete dependencies — you
cannot test LLMEngine without a real OpenAI HTTP call. Distributed wiring is better but swapping
one implementation — changing OpenAIAdapter to AnthropicAdapter — requires finding and
updating every place that instantiates it. A single composition root means exactly one line changes in
exactly one file for any infrastructure swap. It also means the full dependency graph is visible and
inspectable in one place.
Why Inline Instantiation Fails
// WRONG — inline instantiation
class LLMEngine {
private gateway = new OpenAIAdapter(process.env.LLM_URL, process.env.LLM_KEY)
// ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
// LLMEngine is now permanently coupled to OpenAI.
// Cannot test without a real HTTP call.
// Cannot swap providers without modifying LLMEngine.
}
Why Distributed Wiring Fails
// WRONG — wiring spread across multiple files
// In CLIRunner.ts
const llmGateway = new OpenAIAdapter(config.url, config.key) // instantiated here
const llmEngine = new LLMEngine(llmGateway)
// In CICDAdapter.ts
const llmGateway = new OpenAIAdapter(config.url, config.key) // also here
const llmEngine = new LLMEngine(llmGateway)
// Swap to Anthropic: must update CLIRunner.ts AND CICDAdapter.ts
// Add a third entry point: must remember to wire it too
// The graph is not visible in one place
The Single Composition Root
One file is the only place concrete types appear. Everything else imports only interfaces. The
composition root assembles the graph in dependency order: infrastructure first, then gateways, then
use cases, then facades, then the final orchestrator.
// src/composition/CompositionRoot.ts
// The only file in the codebase that imports concrete classes.
export class CompositionRoot {
static build(config: ISessionConfig): SessionOrchestrator {
// 1 — infrastructure (the real world)
const fsReader = new FileSystemReader()
const fsWriter = new FileSystemWriter()
const llmGateway = new OpenAIAdapter(config.llmUrl, config.llmKey)
const forgeRunner = new ForgeRunner()
// 2 — component facades (Reader and Executor are pure infrastructure)
const reader = new Reader(fsReader)
const executor = new Executor(fsWriter)
// 3 — use cases (injected with the gateways they need)
const assemblePrompt = new AssemblePrompt(reader)
const generateInvariants = new GenerateInvariants(llmGateway)
const adaptFoundryConfig = new AdaptFoundryConfig(llmGateway)
const runFuzzer = new RunFuzzer(forgeRunner)
const runCoverage = new RunCoverage(forgeRunner)
const evaluateOutcome = new EvaluateOutcome(reader)
const formatBug = new FormatBugReport()
const formatExhausted = new FormatExhaustedReport()
const formatCoverage = new FormatCoverageReport()
const formatDevTest = new FormatDevTestFailure()
// 4 — component facades (injected with their use cases)
const llmEngine = new LLMEngine(executor, assemblePrompt, generateInvariants,
adaptFoundryConfig)
const foundryEngine = new FoundryEngine(runFuzzer, runCoverage, evaluateOutcome)
const reporter = new Reporter(reader, formatBug, formatExhausted,
formatCoverage, formatDevTest)
// 5 — orchestrator use cases (injected with component facades as ports)
const initialiseSession = new InitialiseSession()
const runRound = new RunRound(llmEngine, foundryEngine)
const checkTermination = new CheckTermination()
// 6 — final assembly
return new SessionOrchestrator(reporter, initialiseSession, runRound,
checkTermination)
}
}
How Entry Points Use It
Entry points call CompositionRoot.build() with config parsed from their delivery mechanism. They
receive a fully assembled SessionOrchestrator and run it. They know nothing about what is inside.
// entry/cli/CLIRunner.ts
class CLIRunner {
run(argv: string[]): void {
const request = this.argParser.parse(argv) // protocol translation
const orchestrator = CompositionRoot.build(request.config) // full graph assembled
orchestrator.run(request) // run the session
}
}
// entry/cicd/CICDAdapter.ts
class CICDAdapter {
run(env: NodeJS.ProcessEnv): void {
const request = this.envReader.parse(env)
const orchestrator = CompositionRoot.build(request.config)
orchestrator.run(request)
}
}
The Verification Tests
Three checks confirm the composition root is working correctly:
• Swapping OpenAIAdapter for AnthropicAdapter requires changing exactly one line in exactly
one file. If it requires more, wiring has leaked out of the composition root.
• Every use case class can be instantiated in a test with mock implementations of its port
interfaces, with zero imports from infrastructure/. If a test needs a real file or a real HTTP
call, the dependency rule has been violated.
• No file outside composition/CompositionRoot.ts imports a concrete infrastructure class. If it
does, that file has assumed wiring responsibility it should not have.
Complete File Structure
The structure below is the direct result of the three decisions above. Every folder and file exists
because of a specific decision. Nothing is added for convention.
Top Level
src/
interfaces/ // D1 — shared I* contracts, no component owns them
orchestrator/ // D1 — component boundary for sequencing
llm/ // D1 — component boundary for LLM interaction
foundry/ // D1 — component boundary for fuzzer execution
reader/ // D1 — component boundary for all file reads
executor/ // D1 — component boundary for all file writes
reporter/ // D1 — component boundary for output formatting
entry/ // D1 — delivery mechanism adapters (CLI, CI/CD)
composition/ // D3 — single wiring point
interfaces/
src/interfaces/
ISessionRequest.ts // Entry point to Orchestrator
IRoundSignal.ts // Orchestrator to LLMEngine / FoundryEngine
ILLMSignal.ts // LLMEngine to Orchestrator
IFuzzReport.ts // FoundryEngine to Orchestrator
ISessionOutcome.ts // Orchestrator to Reporter
ITerminationDecision.ts
ISessionState.ts // Round counter and session config
ISessionConfig.ts // LLM URL, key, output format, CI flag
IContractContext.ts
IFuzzReportContext.ts
ICoverageContext.ts
IInvariantFiles.ts
IReportArtifacts.ts
IInvariantSet.ts
IFoundryConfig.ts
IAssembledPrompt.ts
orchestrator/
src/orchestrator/
SessionOrchestrator.ts // Facade — loop shell, no logic of its own
use_cases/ // D2 — one class per action
InitialiseSession.ts // Builds ISessionState from ISessionRequest
RunRound.ts // Sends IRoundSignal, awaits ILLMSignal + IFuzzReport
CheckTermination.ts // bug | fullCoverage | exhausted | continue
ports/ // D3 — Orchestrator defines what it needs
ILLMEnginePort.ts // run(signal): Promise<ILLMSignal>
IFoundryEnginePort.ts // run(signal): Promise<IFuzzReport>
IReporterPort.ts // emit(outcome): void
llm/
src/llm/
LLMEngine.ts // Facade — implements ILLMEnginePort
use_cases/ // D2 — one class per action
AssemblePrompt.ts // Context weighting and prompt structure
GenerateInvariants.ts // LLM call + Solidity parsing
AdaptFoundryConfig.ts // LLM call + config parsing
ports/ // D3 — LLMEngine defines what it needs
IReaderPort.ts // getContractContext, getFuzzReportContext,
getCoverageContext
IExecutorPort.ts // writeInvariants, writeFoundryConfig
ILLMGateway.ts // call(prompt): Promise<string>
infrastructure/ // D3 — concrete implementations, injected by CompositionRoot
OpenAIAdapter.ts // Implements ILLMGateway
AnthropicAdapter.ts // Implements ILLMGateway — swap with one line change
parsers/
InvariantParser.ts // Raw LLM string to IInvariantSet
ConfigParser.ts // Raw LLM string to IFoundryConfig
foundry/
src/foundry/
FoundryEngine.ts // Facade — implements IFoundryEnginePort
use_cases/ // D2 — one class per action
RunFuzzer.ts // forge test — captures exit code and stdout
RunCoverage.ts // forge coverage — only on exit code 0
EvaluateOutcome.ts // bug | pass | fullCoverage — the critical decision
ports/ // D3 — FoundryEngine defines what it needs
IReaderPort.ts // getInvariantFiles, getFuzzOutput, getLcov
IForgeRunnerPort.ts // runTest(), runCoverage(): Promise<IForgeResult>
infrastructure/ // D3 — concrete implementations
ForgeRunner.ts // Implements IForgeRunnerPort — real subprocess
reader/ and executor/
src/reader/
Reader.ts // Facade — single read gateway
parsers/ // D2 — no use cases, parsers only (no decisions)
ContractParser.ts // Raw Solidity to IContractContext
LcovParser.ts // lcov.info to ICoverageContext
FuzzOutputParser.ts // fuzz_output.txt to IFuzzReportContext
MemoryParser.ts // .fuzzming/memory.json to RAG memory structure
infrastructure/ // D3 — concrete implementations
FileSystemReader.ts // The only class calling fs.readFileSync
src/executor/
Executor.ts // Facade — single write gateway
writers/ // D2 — no use cases, writers only (no decisions)
InvariantWriter.ts // IInvariantSet to test/fuzzming/*.fuzzming.t.sol
FoundryConfigWriter.ts // IFoundryConfig to foundry.toml [profile.fuzzming]
MemoryWriter.ts // Bug findings to .fuzzming/memory.json
infrastructure/ // D3 — concrete implementations
FileSystemWriter.ts // The only class calling fs.writeFileSync
reporter/ | entry/ | composition/
src/reporter/
Reporter.ts // Facade — implements IReporterPort
use_cases/ // D2 — one class per outcome type
FormatBugReport.ts
FormatExhaustedReport.ts
FormatCoverageReport.ts
FormatDevTestFailure.ts
ports/
IReaderPort.ts // getReportArtifacts
IOutputPort.ts // write(output): void — terminal vs PR comment
infrastructure/
TerminalOutput.ts // Implements IOutputPort — stdout
PRCommentOutput.ts // Implements IOutputPort — GitHub/GitLab PR comment
src/entry/
cli/CLIRunner.ts // Controller — argv to ISessionRequest
cli/ArgParser.ts // Knows --target, --rounds, --llm-url, --llm-key
cicd/CICDAdapter.ts // Controller — env vars to ISessionRequest
cicd/EnvReader.ts // Reads process.env — CI env coupling stays here
src/composition/
CompositionRoot.ts // D3 — the only file importing concrete types
